      <tr>
        <td bgcolor="black" valign="top">
        <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">
        
		<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=782">
        	
		<font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"><b>Etadanik Mistmorgue</a>
        </b></font>

        <br><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"><small>Spectre</small></font>

        <br><img src=icon_star_purple.gif border=0><img src=icon_star_purple.gif border=0><img src=icon_star_purple.gif border=0>
        <br>
        <br><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"><small>USA</small></font>
        <br><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"><small>644 Posts</small></font></td>
        <td bgcolor="black" colspan="2"  valign="top">
		<img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;07/15/2002&nbsp;:&nbsp; 23:09:48</font>

		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&amp;id=782"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
 
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=782')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=TopicQuote&amp;TOPIC_ID=6079&amp;FORUM_ID=2&amp;CAT_ID=1&amp;Forum_Title=General+Discussions&amp;Topic_Title=AA+Skills+%2D+A+Discussion"><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height="15" width="15" alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana" size="2"> AA skills: great idea at first sight.  Now level 60's have something to look forward to, and the tread mill of experience seems to have been expanded onto infinity.  I do not recall anyone who has yet reached the _limit_ of AA xp yet, and it's been quite a while since the release of Luclin.  This appears to solve VI's dilemma of having to provide higher advancement for PCs - after all, how hard is it to just add a few hard-to-obtain class-only AA xp skills with each new expansion and call it: new advancement for level 60 characters!? Everything seems rosy enough.</P><P>But then we take a look at the distribution of level 60's across servers, and we see a monster spreading its dreaded wings over all of Norrath:</P><P>Simply put: Overcrowding has again reared its ugly head.</P><P>With the advent of AA xp and the eagerness of all previous exp-grinders to gain some of oh-so-powerful +1 point of stamina, every zone in Norrath and Luclin has to suffer through the seemingly endless pillaging of level 60's - uber guilded or not - whose hunger for AA xp skills lead them to simply crush, destroy, and mortify everything in their path.  Ah, but you ask, isn't it the same even if we didn't have AA xp? Well, not exactly.  You see, it's been my experience that most people who make level 60 pre-Luclin either play twinks, waiting for a raid to happen, or go off doing something they truly enjoy in EQ (or quit EQ, for that matter), rather than trudge endlessly forth in the exp game.  The former helps with the exp distribution of Norrath and allows many otherwise unused newbie zones to go into use, while the latter usually involves creative self-challenges that become the stuff of legends...  </P><P>A further problem is the fact that level 60's AA xping tend to go head on into conflict with mid-high level 50 players trying to exp to 60.  Maiden's Eye, one of the zones I've frequented for the last few months, is now a battleground between level 60 wizards / druids quad kiting gorangas for AA xp, necros fear kiting gorangas, enchanters charm soloing, and low-mid level 50 groups trying to survive.  This does not make for a pretty sight, I assure you.</P><P>Ultimately this is a neutral design problem.  I don't see why level 60's should take care of the lower levels by giving up exp spots to them (though I feel I should give props to those who do), nor why lower levels should do any more for level 60's.  But with PoP on the horizon and supposedly _more_ AAXP skills, I fear that it'll do nothing but worsen the problem.</P><P>This problem is further worsened by the fact that VI is extremely singy with creating good non-raiding zones. (they do fine with those, for some reason)  And it's been getting worse ever since Velious.  The Grey & Maiden's Eye are supposed to be great outdoor zones, but in truth both zones lack the ability to handle a crowd (how many good spots are there in Grey after they added those patrolling worms & shimmering rockfiends? Be honest.  Maidens same thing: whose idea was it to put a coterie camp in the middle of an obscene amount of skeletons? Why put a bunch of traps in an already heavily patrolled area?) Marus Seru? Damn it must've been really difficult to create a zone with one set of textures and nothing interesting for miles.  Let's not even talk about the complete waste of a zone Mons Letalis is (I've just about never seen people hunt there), or the fact that almost no one visits Griegs End, the Deep, or Acrylia other than to raid despite them being interesting zones (risk vs. reward anyone?)</P><P>Two years down the road and two expansions later, where do most people still hunt? Sebilis, Chardok, Karnor Castle.  If they never revamped Velketor or Cazic Thule, those zones would, I imagine, still be unused.  Heck, Siren's Grotto, even after a major revamp, is still underused.</P><P>It all comes down to the potential of PoP in the end.  VI has already admitted that they will concentrate on the "high-end" game - but the definition of "high-end" has changed.  Raids are increasingly becoming less of a concern in terms of the lack of content, while exp zones have become far more of a problem.  Only people in high-end uber guilds worry about not having enough stuff to raid.  But EVERYONE worry about not having a place to exp at 60.  And this problem can only get worse.        </P><P>What VI can do, ideally, in PoP, is to make the majority of the planes either exp zones or half-exp zones (like Sebilis, where raids & pick-up groups coexist), and a smaller percentage (maybe ~20%) pure raid zones like Umbral/VT.  Ideally, they will also implement GOOD raid zones that aren't complete timesinks because they lack staying power otherwise. (Ntov / Plane of Fear are examples of "good" raid zones that people return to, and which do not require six months worth of mind numbingly boring camps to succeed in)  Let's assume PoP comes with 20 zones.  If 10 of those were Sebilis-quality hybrid exp/raid zones, things will be good.  If only two of them are and the rest are all raid / city zones, however, I fear that the end of EQ may come sooner than the release of Shadowbane and World of Warcraft.</P><P></P><P>Etadanik the Redeemed</font></td>

      </tr>

